Asics shouldn't work on registration though
so either they GPU registered, FPGA, or they ran it on lots of CPU
but bitcoin ASICs should not be able to target registration as they do double sha256
the old pow that wasn't keccak would allow asics
and this person registered most of their h/w before that update
so it would be impossible to use one, meaning you'd either need a single sha256 ASIC, or design one yourself

I think the problem is the ASIC design is most efficient when it incorporates combining the blockhash on-chip so the ASIC would need to be designed to add the blockhash and do only a single sha256, where bitcoin Asics (although called sha256) do sha256d, which is double sha256, and therefore don't work

afaik, there aren't any single sha256 coins and therefore no ASICs, but of course I could be mistaken
it is good though that the registration is now more resistant, regardless
Still, GPU is possible.
GPU is possible still, and that's fine because we want to target GPUs
also, the keccak addition won't prevent FPGA either, so that's also still a possibility
POW attacks are easy, and likely will happen often
the idea is to stop attackers from gaining traction once they get in
I think we're doing that well, which is good

If we wanted to limit ASICs and FPGAs, we can either switch to different algos (or stack them) or we can find something very memory heavy that's still parallelizable

ASICs especially and FPGAs have low memory, meaning increasing the memory requirements would make development so much more expensive that it's unlikely anyone would pursue it
but I think it's fine for now anyway

Been busy, so no way to give a clear answer on my questions. But @vune [τ, τ), to answer your question: they get ranked by other validators, but treated as a non-responsive node. Since they never reach a true "zero", they get ranked as the minimum by validators.
This also brings me to the second issue, which is that a node that is not weighted is considered to be a "non-responsive" node, even though it would have responded, and gets a penalty. My validator only ranks my server high when it's being pinged, else it's ranking slowly deminishes. Can't explain why else you would start seeing a saw pattern with good nodes.

it doesn't stop at 600 though, it stops at the end of the epoch, it randomly samples peers during the epoch and ranks them on a moving average, it continues doing this setting weights of the top 600 on the chain until the epoch resets all the averages.
I may be wrong about that, but the best person to ask would be @consτ [τ, τ] or @shibshib

Its not paranoia, it's fact that if you don't have a big machine, you will be fucked over by the system, even if your model is the best out there. You seen the issue with the ASIC miner, that was actually making a profit by simply spamming enough keys on the network so that they got into the top-600 rankings. If you dump a shitty validator on the network that only validates 10% of the network at a given time, it will screw the other 90% of the network. Yes, it will go over all the nodes at a given time, no worries about that. It will however declare you 9 times a "non-responsive node" though, and 9/10 times you will not be in its top-600. And the shapely factor does smooth the average out, but if you get hit 9 out of 10 times with a "non-responsive", you really need a good server to counter that. Also, if a big whale does not ping the whole network in a single sitting, that whale can actually push small fry off the network for calling non-pinged nodes as "non-responsive", just because they never checked that node. If that validator only does a full pass every 30-40 minutes, you will be screwed over if you miss that moment, no matter what you are running.

Its similar to what I have seen with GenSyn. A lot of claims, but the question i find most important is: Does it solve anything that cannot be solved with what we have now? Eg: Bittensor is a framework designed around distributed model optimalisation. This means that the chain itself can be forked, changed or even redesigned. Technically speaking, I can even make a clone out of bittensor for creating what I tend to call the "modron hive".
These things like Giza and GenSyn are all based on a L2 basis: They use Etherium as their basis for their model. They all need Etherium to function, they don't have their own blockchain, they use an existing blockchain and slap their own code on it. The issue with that is that when something goes awfully wrong with Etherium, you also have something going awfully wrong with their code. And if the prices of Etherium skyrocket, so will their training...

the paper for this

```Gato was inspired by works such as GPT-3 (Brown et al., 2020) and Gopher (Rae et al., 2021),
pushing the limits of generalist language models; and more recently the Flamingo (Alayrac et al.,
2022) generalist visual language model. Chowdhery et al. (2022) developed the 540B parameter
Pathways Language Model (PalM) explicitly as a generalist few-shot learner for hundreds of text tasks.
Future work should consider how to unify these text capabilities into one fully generalist agent that
can also act in real time in the real world, in diverse environments and embodiments.```
